Standard MAGSAT method calibrations were performed in the 22-foot facility using the following procedure: 
The facility was adjusted to zero field and checked using (reversals of) a magnetic sensor at the origin.
The MOB was positioned in orientation #1 using lasers for coarse alignment and then adjusting the orientation of the MOB until autocollimation with both theodolites was achieved with an accuracy of ∼2 arcsec.
Data was acquired for 20 s in zero applied field in instrument dynamic ranges 6, 5, 4.
A facility field of ∼70,000 nT was applied sequentially in both polarities and along all three facility axes and for each applied field the sensor response, averaged over 20 s, in instrument dynamic ranges (6, 5, 4) was recorded. The field magnitude was also continuously recorded at a reference position ∼1 m from the test article using a reference proton precession magnetometer (PPM1).
A facility field of ∼22,000 nT was applied in both polarities and along all three facility axes and for each applied field the sensor response, averaged over 20 s, in instrument dynamic ranges (4, 2) was recorded. The field magnitude was also continuously recorded at a reference position ∼1 m from the test article using a reference proton precession magnetometer (PPM1).
Steps 3–5 were repeated after repositioning the MOB in orientation #2 using lasers for coarse alignment and then adjusting the orientation of the MOB until autocollimation with both theodolites was achieved with an accuracy of ∼2 arcsec.
Steps 3–5 were repeated after repositioning the MOB in orientation #4 using lasers for coarse alignment and then adjusting the orientation of the MOB until autocollimation with both theodolites was achieved with an accuracy of ∼2 arcsec.
Measurements for sensor zero determination were obtained by commanding the facility back to zero field and performing a series of reversals (180° rotations about sensor x\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
