The non-magnetic micro Advanced Stellar Compass (μASC) is a fully autonomous high performance non-magnetic star tracker, evolved from the Oersted, SAC-C, CHAMP, and SMART-1 instruments. Despite its miniature size, it implements four fully independent star trackers, backed by a powerful and fully hardware redundant data processing unit (DPU). A block diagram of the system appears in Fig. 27. The μASC requires minimal spacecraft resources (mass, volume and power consumption) and provides accurate attitude solutions with high reliability; consequently, this star tracker is currently found on more than 50 spacecraft. Fig. 27
Schematic block diagram of the ASC electronics. All Camera Head Units (CHUs) may be powered when instrument power is applied, via one of the power converter/digital logic blocks (‘A\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
